AGI -&nbsp; The body of Giulio Regeni has been found "almost all the tortures put in place in Egypt and described, including fists, kicks, use of bats, burns". Professor Vittorio Fineschi, a specialist in legal medicine and attorney of the prosecutor of Rome, reported this in the courtroom during a new hearing of the trial on the murder, kidnapping and torture of the Italian researcher, for which four 007 Egyptians are accused. Fineschi followed the autopsy on the body of the 28-year-old researcher of Friulian origin, kidnapped in Cairo on January 25, 2016 and found dead body on February 3, following the road connecting the Egyptian capital to Alexandria:&nbsp; "The legal medical checks carried out in Egypt were under the minimum standard - said today in the court responding to the questions of the attorney added Sergio Colaiocco - what they describe is not found. Legal medical checks in Egypt have been incomplete and undetermined." Egypt - the specialist in audience has explained - "in the course of the years has published two scientific works on torture, of which one relative to 140 cases with the list of modalities of tortures placed in existence on the living, as people arrested and then tortured also with dragging the body, bats, handcuffs and ankles, burns. In another publication - said Fineschi - that is a retrospective study of 367 cases of torture occurred in the years 2009 and 2010 in Egypt are reported many modalities of torture that were then found also on the body of Giulio Regeni, for example the basates on the feet until the fracture of all bones".&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Regeni's death can be "stated between 22:00 on January 31 and 22:00 on February 2, 2016". This was reported in the courtroom by the toxicologist Marcello Chiarotti. The findings of the Prosecutor's technical advisor were carried out on 6 February 2016, when a sample of "umor vitreo" was taken to assess the potassium level in the post-mortem phase. The death of the boy would rise to "124 hours of the withdrawal", an average value between a minimum range of 96 hours and a maximum of 150 hours. Giulio, moreover, had not made any use of any astounding substance or drugs or poisonous substances: "Toxicological investigations have all failed," explained Chiarotti.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2 The lawyer of the Regeni family, today will be a painful hearing
"Today's will be a particularly harsh and painful hearing, because it will be represented and recounted meticulously all the evil of the world that has fallen on Giulio. We asked for a part to run through closed doors, so it will be. Because we don't want anyone who loved Giulio, his friends and family, to remember him as he will be shown. We ask all of you that no one spread those images, because it would be an outrage to all those who loved him and Giulio's dignity." That's what lawyer Alessandra Ballerini, a lawyer from Giulio Regeni's family, told the sit-in that Piazzale Clodio took place a few minutes before the trial hearing on the researcher's murder. In the process, which is celebrated in front of the court of Assisi of Rome, four 007 Egyptians are charged. Present in the square in front of the Capitoline judiciary also some students of the Tito Lucrezio Caro high school in Rome. The young people read some passages from the book "Giulio does things", written by Giulio Regeni's parents along with lawyer Ballerini: "We thank them immensely - said Paola Deffendi and Claudio Regeni - among other things they chose parts of the book not casual, they did it with the heart. They recognize themselves in the figure of Giulio". Today, in the classroom, a doctor and a toxicologist will be heard.&nbsp;
